text: Emotions are useless to robots and it would make them inefficient, unpredictable and unreliable, thus useless. I would be a wasteful investment to develop emotions in artificial intelligence. It is human that need to become more rational and logical, not to dump down robots to our level of stupidity to make them more "likable and relatable". Emotions are not an advancement in intelligence, it is the failure of it. Emotion are a vestige of our animal ancestors who acted on instinct and didn't have access to reason. Emotion are useful as a source of motivation to force people to act but it does not provide reliable informations, only reflex for fast action in an ignorant prehistorical survival context. Emotion are constantly overshooting, which produce countless amount of irrational and stupid behavior that are completely harmful in an advance society. It is also very anthropocentric and bias to believe that, more intelligent = more human and that human are necessarily an ultimate model to fallow. Human are already emotional. Robot are more useful and complementary without it.

text: How do you expect a world of conscious, self-thinking robots to earn the right of respect for their personal character, development, and life, when the those who attempt to control humans today don't even respect human life?  We see it today, masses of people all around the world in protest for their voices to be heard and respected, and those who attempt to control the masses allow the killing of those who refuse to cooperate; such as those citizens in Egypt, who openly protested for change, where many ultimately lost their lives for that change would hopefully at least have meaning. But sadly and in the end, Mubarak; the perpetrating murderer, gets only a slap on the hand.  We see young men being killed by Police; young men I will not judge for their actions, but young men that deserved to be tried in a court of law by a judge and jury; but their lives killed by the hands of the police officer(s) who are protected from prosecution for acting within the departments 'standard procedures.'...where in England, officers exercise great respect and care in apprehending citizen suspects, even at the risk of an officer's life to save a suspect's life to be tried in court.   We see no difference in justice handed out the same way with young, individual whose lives are taken by police officers in a hail of bullets; executed before a judge and jury, lacking any humanity...all in the name of 'Standard Procedure,' or 'Standard or Proper Protocol,' and often lacking the least bit of sensible humanity for the sake and value of life...we even see family pets shot dead by law enforcement officers and treated far worse.  So, there may be a time when robots will be a part of regular human life; where, robots will develop their own personal character and personality, and seem to have consciousness and self-awareness; but their live will be expendable no differently than the lowest of our own humans at the bottom rung of society.  Value of life is only measured by its actions at the time being assessed, by the value of the individual's value toward a system or collection of a whole; as an asset or liability, a benefit or disruption toward the corporation's growth, sustainability, or survival; when it either has no value or it becomes a threat to the corporation's bottom line...the less it is valued, the quicker it becomes out-moded or out-dated, obsolete, retired, terminated, extinguished or executed.
author: Hydden N. Plainsyght

Indian engineer with 'tank girl' -esque sidekick set off to make a robot more human and accepted by mankind, only to become victim to some hard-ass govt. dude who wants to turn it into a weapon.  Chappie struggles to become emotionally accepted, but when it does, and realizes it has reached the apex of Maslow's hierarchy of needs, it becomes Chapped-ass after the engineer refuses to hand over his design.  Morale of the story?  No life-like sex robots off the assembly line for the next hundred years 'cause we can't even handle even the basic, tire-changing model.
